Scenario 7: Denial of Service Attack Against Critical Infrastructure
Background
A hacktivist group launches a distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack against a power grid's control systems, causing rolling blackouts affecting 2 million people. The group claims the attack is a protest against government policies. The attack lasts 6 hours before being mitigated. No one is physically harmed, but economic losses exceed $100 million.

Key Details
•	Target: Critical infrastructure (power grid)
•	Attack Type: DDoS against control systems
•	Duration: 6 hours
•	Impact: 2 million people without power, $100 million in economic losses
•	Attackers: Hacktivist group with political motivations
•	Evidence: Server logs, network traffic, social media communications
•	Legal Questions: Terrorism charges, computer fraud, political speech protections
•	Motivation: Political protest against government policies

Analysis Questions
	Should this attack be prosecuted as terrorism or computer fraud?
	What is the threshold for critical infrastructure attacks to be considered terrorism?
	How should political motivation affect prosecution decisions?
	What are the legal and ethical implications of charging hacktivists?
	Should the investigation focus on identifying individuals or the group?
	What preventive measures should critical infrastructure operators implement?
	How should the government balance national security with civil liberties?
	What role should international cooperation play in investigation?
